narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I developed my mathematical knowledge and critical reasoning skills. I also learned to develop a mathematical "intuition" and how to think more like a mathematician.
Basic and introductory calculus skills. Quick catch up on pre calculus topics like log laws.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: Course is well-organized and Professor Dhillon held plenty of office hours to make sure students felt comfortable with the material. 
Weaknesses: None.

Strengths: The modules are well organized and helpful. The textbook is generally pretty good. The material by nature isn't very interactive but Professor Dhillon did the job and explained the topics fairly well and in a different way to the textbook. Class didn't feel like a repeat of the pre-class watching, which sometimes is the case for other summer session classes.

Weaknesses: The class moves quickly and if you don't have a very strong pre-calculus background in topics like trig functions and logs then you will have to work to catch up. The Friday workshops are group work which can be extremely hit or miss, especially over Zoom. Sometimes homework and pre-class watching would be posted late, making it difficult to manage time.
Very good. I think the university should allow students who don't take ap courses to take higher level class.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, I would, if the student wants a solid introduction to the wonders of calculus. The course truly opens up a world of pathways to understanding the natural world.

I would only recommend this to students who need to take this for a requirement, as the fast pace of the summer class can be stressful. That said, the amount of homework is generally manageable compared to some other summer classes I have taken, so if you have some background in basic differentiation and antidifferentiation, or if you have a very strong pre calculus background, then you might want to take this to get it out of the way. Be aware the exams are very challenging and fast paced and you need to not only be familiar with the material but also able to think on your feet.
Yes. I think it is a good chance for me to learn more about math in this summer.

narratives.question_text: The Canvas course site allowed me to identify and access required course materials easily.
